 darted through lawns as the cop gave chase. Much later, when David was bleeding to death, did the cops realize they had hit one of their own-the son of a fellow cop.Borderline illiterate at the time of the shooting, David took his future into his own hands and found salvation in books. But his attempts to improve his life were stymied by lack of familial support. Bound on all sides by adults who had no faith in his ability to learn or to succeed, David persevered and earned his Ph.D.Funny and poignant, but always honest and reflective, A Shot Story tracks David Borkowski's life before and after the "accident" and tells how his having been a rather unremarkable student may have been a blessing in disguise. A wonderful addition to the working-class narrative genre, A Shot Story presents a gripping account of the silences of working-class culture as well as the male subculture of Staten Island. Through his heartfelt memoir, Borkowski explores the universal lesson of turning a wrong into a rite of passage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCollege teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aEducationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitationzUnited States. 0aLife change eventszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAutodidact.  aLiteracy.  adeath.  aeducation.  aepiphany.  aprodigy.  aredemption.  aworking-class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823266012?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823266012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823266012/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBAC